  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface for a Buddhist Ceremony to Avert Disaster
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven's Way is lofty and luminous, silently portending extraordinary calamities. Buddha's compassion runs deep and vast, able to bestow the power to dispel all fear. We must earnestly cultivate virtue and make offerings, that we may receive blessings and benefit.

    Reflecting upon myself, unworthy as I am, I hold this throne in shame. I cannot embody the supreme principle of Spring and Autumn to nourish all living things, nor can I employ the Five Matters of the Great Plan to harmonize the celestial signs. Day and night I meditate in dread, as one treading upon thin ice above an abyss.

    Yet the royal astronomers report: the heavens present fearsome omens. Red vapors surge upward to pierce the sky; white halos circle round the sun itself, drawing ever closer. I cannot fathom what calamity these portents herald, nor can I grasp the workings of fate. To forestall the approaching catastrophe, I must turn humbly to the Buddha's way.

    Thus we perform these sacred rites and reverently present fragrant offerings. We bow before the Buddha's radiant countenance and recite the subtle teachings of his precious dharma. May this sincere devotion reach the Buddha's all-seeing wisdom.

    I humbly pray: may ten thousand celestial spirits protect us; may a hundred blessings manifest and be fulfilled. Grant that this humble one may long preserve the fortune of health and peace. May the imperial palace gather good fortune, may serenity crystallize in the palace gardens. May the royal lineage endure as eternal as the Southern Mountains; may the realm's fortune extend from the eastern gates. May our people live in harmony, all turning toward prosperity and long life. May the frontiers know peace, never witnessing the scourge of war. May wind and rain favor our lands as they blessed the age of sage-kings; may granaries overflow with abundance as in the golden Zhou dynasty.
  footnotes:
    - '春秋一元 (Spring and Autumn''s supreme principle): A reference to the cosmological principle found in Confucian thought, representing the fundamental unity from which all things emanate and are nourished.'
    - '洪範五事 (Five Matters of the Great Plan): A concept from the Book of History referring to five governmental and moral principles—appearance, speech, vision, hearing, and thought—whose proper exercise produces harmonious celestial signs.'
    - '日官 (Royal astronomer): The official responsible for observing and interpreting celestial phenomena as indicators of the state''s virtue or deficiency.'
    - '赤祲、白暈 (Red vapors and white halos): Specific celestial omens interpreted in medieval East Asian astrology as warnings of disaster or disharmony in the realm.'
    - '南山、周家 (Southern Mountains, Zhou dynasty): Classical allusions to permanence and abundance—the mountains representing stability, and the Zhou representing a golden age of prosperity and good governance.'
